===Etymology===
A word of Indian origin: compare Spanish ''hamaca''. Columbus, in the narrative of his first voyage, says: "A great many Indians in canoes came to the ship to-day for the purpose of bartering their cotton, and '''hamacas''', or nets, in which they sleep."
===Noun===
#A swinging couch or bed, usually made of netting or canvas about six feet wide, suspended by clews or cords at the ends.
#''(Southern U. S.):'' A piece of land thickly wooded, and usually covered with bushes and vines. Used also adjectively; as, '''hammock''' land. - [[Bartlett]]
===Derived expressions===
*'''Hammock nettings''' ''(Nautical):'' formerly, nets for stowing hammocks; later, more often, wooden boxes or a trough on the rail, used for that purpose.

